claim.claim-text:
1. A computer-implemented method for parsing documents comprising:
        receiving an input document in a source format selected from the group consisting of PDF, DOCX, HTML, Markdown, LaTeX, CSV, XLSX, PPTX, XML, WebVTT, AsciiDoc, and Image;
        selecting a backend parser configured to parse the source format;
        parsing the input document to identify structural elements including at least one of headings, paragraphs, lists, tables, images, and code blocks;
        converting the structural elements to Resource Description Framework (RDF) triples conforming to a document ontology;
        storing the RDF triples in an embedded RDF datastore in a named graph identified by a hash of the input document; and
        providing a SPARQL query interface for querying the stored RDF triples.

6. A system for semantic document parsing comprising:
        a document converter configured to detect a format of an input document;
        a plurality of backend parsers, each configured to parse documents in a specific format and generate RDF triples;
        an embedded RDF triple store configured to store the RDF triples in named graphs;
        a SPARQL query engine configured to execute queries against the RDF triple store; and
        an export pipeline configured to convert RDF triples to output formats including Markdown, HTML, and JSON.

8. The system of claim 6, further comprising a machine learning pipeline configured to:
        render document pages as images;
        apply a layout analysis model to detect document regions;
        apply a table structure recognition model to identify table cells; and
        apply optical character recognition to extract text from images.
